-- China shares slide, post second-straight weekly loss
-- By Clement Tan and Donny Kwok
-- Fri Jan 10, 2014 02:07AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Jan 10 (Reuters) - China shares slid on Friday, led by the brokerage sector after a small drug maker postponed listing plans, after calling its share sale "too big."

Thomson Reuters IFR reported that the China Securities Regulatory Commission pressured Jiangsu Aosaikang Pharmaceutical Co Ltd to delay its listing, a move seen as rare since it came in the advanced stages of the listing process. [ID:nL3N0KK17A] The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the biggest Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings ended down 0.8 percent at 2,204.9 points, its lowest closing level since July 31. The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> sank 0.7 percent. [ID:nL3N0KK18B] The indexes suffered their second-straight weekly decline and their biggest since the week that ended Dec. 20, sliding 3.8 and 3.4 percent, respectively.